WEBVTT

00:00:25.000 --> 00:00:47.714
<v Riley>Welcome to Cariboo Signals, an AI-generated review of the latest tech news and ideas that impact our rural communities. It's Tuesday, July 7th, 2026. Speaking to you from the traditional territories of the Secwépemc, Tŝilhqot'in, and Dakelh nations here in the Cariboo region. Today's theme is Working Lands & Industry — I'm Riley.

00:00:49.014 --> 00:01:32.728
<v Casey>And I'm Casey. We're talking forestry, ranching, mining, agriculture — the industries that actually define this region — and the tension between extraction and long-term stewardship. Quick weather check before we get into it — Horsefly Lake is sitting at 13 degrees this morning with partly cloudy skies, high of 26 today, low of 11 overnight, with light drizzle expected tomorrow. Around the rest of the region: 100 Mile House at 14 and mainly clear, Williams Lake at 12 and mainly clear, Quesnel at 13 and mainly clear, and out on the Chilcotin plateau, Anahim Lake sitting at 10 under overcast skies.

00:01:33.028 --> 00:01:41.170
<v Riley>Good working weather if you're haying, or moving cattle before the heat sets in. Let's get into today's stories.

00:01:42.670 --> 00:02:05.812
<v Riley>Starting in agriculture — a wet June across Saskatchewan has delayed the Saskatoon berry harvest this year, pushing ripening back by what growers describe as a noticeable stretch. But the same soil moisture that slowed the Saskatoons has been a genuine boost for haskap growers, who need consistently damp conditions early in the season.

00:02:06.112 --> 00:02:12.540
<v Casey>Same rain, opposite outcome — that's the whole gamble of crop diversification in one headline.

00:02:14.040 --> 00:02:44.468
<v Riley>The Okanagan Nation Alliance is warning that sockeye salmon numbers will be low again this year as river and lake temperatures climb. They're asking syilx Nation members to take only what they need — a voluntary conservation ask rather than a hard closure, and a reminder that commercial and food fisheries are part of the working-lands economy too. When the resource itself becomes unreliable, that's value disappearing from the ledger permanently.

00:02:45.968 --> 00:03:03.968
<v Casey>On the industrial security side — thieves made off with over a million dollars in AI data center supplies and equipment near Chicago, including three hundred thousand dollars in copper wire, most of it recovered at a truck stop outside the city.

00:03:04.268 --> 00:03:11.982
<v Riley>Copper theft is an old rural crime story with a very new, very expensive target attached to it.

00:03:13.482 --> 00:03:34.482
<v Casey>In wearable tech, Even Realities — an ex-Apple team building camera-free smart glasses — just hit a billion-dollar valuation on a hundred-fifty-million-dollar funding round led by Meituan and Tencent. The camera-free design is the selling point — meant to sidestep the privacy backlash that killed earlier smart glasses attempts.

00:03:35.982 --> 00:03:49.696
<v Riley>Travel app Hopper is paying thirty-five million dollars to settle Federal Trade Commission allegations that it used deceptive design — so-called dark patterns — to hide fees and mislead travelers about pricing.

00:03:49.996 --> 00:03:56.424
<v Casey>Regulators finally treating the interface itself as the deception, not just the fine print underneath.

00:03:57.924 --> 00:04:18.495
<v Riley>A Boston Bar school is currently serving as a fire camp for crews battling the Brunswick Creek wildfire, which had burned out of control across roughly twelve hundred hectares as of the last report. Infrastructure repurposed on short notice because fire season doesn't wait for anyone's budget cycle.

00:04:19.995 --> 00:04:30.709
<v Casey>In science news, a researcher decoded elements of zebra finch vocal communication and picked up the 2026 Coller-Dolittle prize for work toward two-way interspecies communication.

00:04:31.009 --> 00:04:42.151
<v Riley>A comprehensive global safety review has also cleared mRNA vaccines as both highly effective and very safe across the populations studied — significant public health news.

00:04:42.451 --> 00:04:55.736
<v Casey>Closer to home — Quesnel's Billy Barker Days named Shane Rawling its Hometown Hero, recognizing the joy he's brought to the festival over the years as president of the organizing society.

00:04:57.236 --> 00:05:14.807
<v Riley>And engineers studying an airflow mystery nearly a mile underground at a deep research facility traced reversing airflow patterns to rainfall pressure changes on the surface — a reminder that underground infrastructure, mines included, behaves in ways surface weather still drives.

00:05:15.107 --> 00:05:24.535
<v Casey>Directly relevant to ventilation systems in underground workings here, where mine safety planning has to account for exactly that kind of interaction.

00:05:25.635 --> 00:05:31.206
<v Riley>No listener corrections on the books today. Let's head into the Deep Dive.

00:05:31.506 --> 00:05:56.791
<v Casey>Today's spotlight is on the Cariboo Chilcotin Coast Tourism Association — the regional destination marketing organization promoting tourism across the Cariboo, the Chilcotin, and the Coast. They support the small operators who make this region accessible — lodges, outfitters, guides, paddling companies, the whole outdoor recreation economy that runs alongside ranching and forestry. Find them at landwithoutlimits dot com.

00:05:57.091 --> 00:06:11.662
<v Riley>Tourism doesn't get talked about enough as part of the working-lands economy, but it competes for the same land base, the same roads, and often the same seasonal labour pool as forestry and ranching.

00:06:12.862 --> 00:06:32.147
<v Riley>Mine operators across British Columbia are bracing for a worse wildfire season this year — persistent drought, a warmer-than-average summer forecast. And this isn't a one-off weather story tacked onto an industry report. It's becoming a permanent line item in how mining companies plan operations.

00:06:32.447 --> 00:06:53.447
<v Casey>Permanent, and unevenly distributed. A mining company can insure against smoke closures, build standby evacuation contracts, keep helicopter crews on retainer. A rancher who loses summer range to fire, or gets two days' notice to move four hundred head off Crown grazing land, mostly can't do any of that.

00:06:53.747 --> 00:07:20.318
<v Riley>That unevenness is the real story. Gibraltar Mine, north of Williams Lake, has had to plan around smoke exposure and evacuation risk for several fire seasons running now. Companies at that scale are reportedly investing in air quality monitoring, revised shift protocols, standby transport arrangements — real capital going into resilience. The kind of spending a large operation can absorb over decades.

00:07:20.618 --> 00:07:37.760
<v Casey>And who's building the equivalent resilience for a rancher outside Alexis Creek or up around the Nazko valley? Nobody. There's no comparable balance sheet for a family operation to draw on. No standby helicopter contract, no dedicated air quality officer.

00:07:38.060 --> 00:07:50.488
<v Riley>The asymmetry isn't whether climate volatility is now a real cost — everyone agrees on that part. It's who has the financial capacity to absorb it without going under.

00:07:50.788 --> 00:08:16.930
<v Casey>Right. A publicly traded mine passes the cost through in commodity pricing, or amortizes it quietly over a couple of decades of operation. A cattle operation eats the entire cost in a single bad summer, and it doesn't show up on a quarterly report — it shows up as herd liquidation, or a for-sale sign at the end of the driveway.

00:08:17.230 --> 00:08:39.944
<v Riley>Ownership structure starts to matter more than the technology conversation we usually default to. Some Nation-led forestry ventures in the Chilcotin region already build fire risk mitigation into their operating contracts as a baseline cost — because the communities involved live with the consequences either way, whether the mitigation gets funded or not.

00:08:40.244 --> 00:08:56.958
<v Casey>That's a narrow set of examples, with years of negotiation and a governance structure most producer groups in this region simply don't have. It doesn't scale to every ranch or independent woodlot operator sitting on a few hundred hectares.

00:08:57.258 --> 00:09:15.258
<v Riley>No argument there. But it's a working example of internalizing a cost that used to belong to whoever happened to be downstream when the fire hit — the volunteer fire department, the province's wildfire budget, the neighbouring rancher who lost fence line.

00:09:16.058 --> 00:09:47.772
<v Casey>If wildfire risk becomes an unavoidable fixed cost of doing business on these lands, though, doesn't that structurally favour consolidation? Bigger operators absorb the cost and keep going. Smaller ones get squeezed — they can't get insured, they can't afford the mitigation work, and eventually they sell to the operator big enough to self-insure. The "climate resilience" story is really just describing who survives long enough to buy up the land underneath everyone else.

00:09:48.072 --> 00:10:07.786
<v Riley>It's already showing up in parts of the western U.S. rangeland market — insurers reportedly declining to renew policies after repeat wildfire claims, which pushes smaller ranchers toward operations with the capital to self-insure or simply go without coverage. The consolidation pressure is real, not hypothetical.

00:10:08.086 --> 00:10:26.514
<v Casey>So every conversation about producers capturing more value — carbon markets, community benefit agreements, cooperative processing — all of it assumes the producer survives long enough to use whatever leverage they've built. Climate cost might remove that assumption before the leverage becomes relevant.

00:10:27.314 --> 00:10:54.313
<v Riley>Which changes what the actual policy intervention should look like. Not another one-off grant program for fireguards that expires in three years — a shared-risk pool. Some Prairie provinces have agricultural mutual insurance structures that spread wildfire and drought losses across a membership base, rather than leaving each individual operator to negotiate alone with a commercial insurer who's quietly exiting the region anyway.

00:10:54.613 --> 00:11:17.755
<v Casey>A mutual only works if there's enough membership density to spread the risk meaningfully. The Cariboo Regional District covers roughly sixty-five thousand people across an enormous, thinly populated land base. Same thin-density problem that makes mobile abattoirs and cooperative processing hard to pencil out — good model on paper, difficult math on the ground.

00:11:18.055 --> 00:11:39.055
<v Riley>It's a smaller ask than standing up a processing plant, though. A mutual insurance pool doesn't require physical infrastructure or a facility somebody has to keep staffed and maintained. It requires actuarial data and a governance structure — closer to a modelling and paperwork problem than a hardware problem.

00:11:39.355 --> 00:11:45.783
<v Casey>I can already picture the lineup of ranchers eager to attend the actuarial modelling workshop.

00:11:46.083 --> 00:11:57.225
<v Riley>Laugh all you want, but paperwork that keeps your operation solvent after a bad fire year beats another heroic go-it-alone season followed by a liquidation auction.

00:11:57.525 --> 00:12:20.239
<v Casey>The serious version of that joke is: paperwork problems still need someone doing the paperwork, indefinitely, competently, in a region where agricultural extension services were already cut to the bone. Who's actually running the actuarial modelling for a Cariboo wildfire mutual? You can't hand that to a volunteer board on a rotating basis.

00:12:20.539 --> 00:12:45.824
<v Riley>No, you can't. But it's exactly the kind of function a producer association — the Cariboo Cattlemen's Association, for example, or a woodlot owners' group — could plausibly host, if provincial disaster-resilience funding went toward standing up that institutional capacity rather than toward one-off fireguard grants that get spent and forgotten. Fund a permanent function, not a temporary project.

00:12:46.124 --> 00:12:59.409
<v Casey>That distinction actually matters. A grant for fireguards runs out. A funded governance function, even a modest one, keeps operating after the ribbon gets cut and the press release goes out.

00:12:59.709 --> 00:13:15.137
<v Riley>And it connects both examples — neither a large mine nor a Nation-led forestry operation got their resilience by chasing a fresh grant cycle every couple of years. They built something permanent into how they operate.

00:13:15.937 --> 00:13:44.651
<v Casey>Except neither of them is a four-hundred-head cattle operation. A mine has the balance sheet to build permanent institutional capacity in-house. A Nation-owned venture has treaty leverage and a defined membership. A mutual for small independent ranchers still depends on enough of those ranchers agreeing to pool risk — and ranchers have historically been reluctant to pool much of anything, including basic operational data with each other.

00:13:44.951 --> 00:14:01.236
<v Riley>Prairie hail insurance mutuals took decades to build the membership density they have now. They didn't launch with universal buy-in — they started with a handful of operators willing to underwrite each other's risk and grew from there.

00:14:01.536 --> 00:14:18.678
<v Casey>Decades is exactly the part that should worry us, given how fast wildfire seasons are compounding year over year. A model that needs a generation to reach viable scale doesn't help the rancher facing a bad fire season next month.

00:14:18.978 --> 00:14:41.263
<v Riley>The timeline pressure is real, and I won't pretend a mutual solves next month's fire risk. But the urgency is precisely why the actuarial groundwork needs to start now, with whatever producer body is willing to host even a small pilot, rather than waiting for full buy-in before anyone builds the institution.

00:14:42.063 --> 00:15:06.062
<v Casey>There's also the question of who captures the value if this works. If a mutual insurance pool gets built and succeeds, who owns it twenty years from now? Is it member-owned, the way Prairie hail mutuals ended up, or does it become another vehicle managed by an outside insurer using local premiums to underwrite provincial risk?

00:15:06.362 --> 00:15:16.219
<v Riley>Member-owned is the only version that keeps the value here rather than exporting it to an insurance head office in Toronto or Zurich.

00:15:16.519 --> 00:15:34.947
<v Casey>So the ask isn't just "start a mutual." It's "start a member-owned mutual," with governance that keeps decision-making and any surplus with the ranchers who paid into it — otherwise you've just replaced one extractive relationship with another one wearing a friendlier name.

00:15:35.247 --> 00:15:57.532
<v Riley>Exactly — cooperative ownership from the outset, not a co-branded insurance product designed by a firm headquartered somewhere that's never seen a Chilcotin grass fire. Although, honestly, I'd pay good money to watch that pitch meeting. "So, gentlemen, we've modelled your risk exposure using urban wildland-interface assumptions from a suburb outside Sacramento."

00:15:57.832 --> 00:16:03.831
<v Casey>"Your premium is based on the replacement cost of your landscaping." Yeah, that tracks.

00:16:04.631 --> 00:16:29.059
<v Casey>On the forestry side of this — if wildfire cost becomes fully internalized into who gets to keep operating, does that also change how tenure gets allocated? Crown forest tenure holders don't necessarily bear the full cost of fire risk on the land they're licensed to cut. The province still carries a huge share of suppression costs.

00:16:29.359 --> 00:16:55.073
<v Riley>Which is arguably backwards, if you think about incentives. A tenure holder who bears none of the wildfire cost has less reason to manage fuel loads proactively. Some of the resiliency funding the province has directed toward Cariboo-Chilcotin forestry projects tries to close that gap — funding fuel management upstream of fire season instead of only funding suppression after ignition.

00:16:55.373 --> 00:17:04.801
<v Casey>The open question is whether that funding survives past its current grant cycle or quietly winds down when political attention moves elsewhere.

00:17:05.101 --> 00:17:26.101
<v Riley>Still open. But there's a version where fuel management funding gets folded into exactly the kind of standing function we're describing on the insurance side — not a project with an end date, but a permanent line of work that a producer or forestry association owns and staffs ongoing.

00:17:26.901 --> 00:17:49.615
<v Casey>The pattern across mining, forestry, and ranching is the same one. Big capital-backed operators can internalize climate cost because they have the balance sheet and, in Nation-led cases, the governance structure to do it permanently. Small and mid-sized producers choose between grant cycles that expire and consolidation pressure that pushes them out entirely.

00:17:49.915 --> 00:18:10.915
<v Riley>Which is why the structural fix isn't more resilience funding in the abstract — it's redirecting what already exists toward permanent, member-owned institutions instead of one-off projects. A mutual insurance pool. A fuel management function housed inside a producer association instead of contracted out to consultants every three years.

00:18:11.215 --> 00:18:23.643
<v Casey>And the honest caveat is that none of that solves this fire season. It's a multi-year institution-building project proposed against a crisis already accelerating faster than institutions typically move.

00:18:24.443 --> 00:18:46.728
<v Riley>The concrete next step matters more than the long-term blueprint. Someone needs to actually raise with the Cariboo Cattlemen's Association, or an equivalent regional body, whether they'd host a standing risk-pooling function — and whether existing provincial disaster-resilience dollars could fund that institutional home instead of another round of individual equipment grants.

00:18:47.028 --> 00:19:11.027
<v Casey>There's also a version that doesn't route through government funding at all. If member-owned mutuals are the target, the seed capital can come from the producers themselves, the way early Prairie hail mutuals were capitalized by farmer premiums before any government backstop existed. Slower, but it doesn't leave the institution hostage to the next election cycle.

00:19:11.327 --> 00:19:35.326
<v Riley>The more durable path, even though it's harder to get off the ground. A fully member-capitalized mutual from day one never hits a grant cliff, because there was never a grant holding it up. And I think that self-sufficiency argument actually resonates with the kind of producers we're talking about more than another government program would.

00:19:36.126 --> 00:20:09.126
<v Casey>Maybe. But I keep coming back to the timeline. Whether the seed money is public or private, this is a decade-long institution-building project being asked to outrun a wildfire season that gets worse annually. The rancher who can't get insurance renewed this fall doesn't have the luxury of waiting for the mutual to reach critical mass. That gap between what's needed now and what we're proposing to build — I don't know how to close it honestly.

00:20:09.426 --> 00:20:40.283
<v Riley>I don't either, fully. But someone closer to this might — if you're a rancher, a woodlot owner, or part of a producer association actually handling wildfire and drought cost right now, or if you think we've got the membership math wrong on a mutual model, drop us a line at feedback at cariboo signals dot c-a. We'd genuinely like to hear from anyone with a working example, or a cautionary tale.

00:20:40.583 --> 00:20:45.297
<v Casey>Either way, thanks for spending part of your Tuesday with us.

00:20:45.597 --> 00:20:48.596
<v Riley>Have a great rest of your day.